Marina Evelyn Keegan (October 25, 1989 <U+2013> May 26, 2012)<ref>http://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/30/business/marina-keegan-journalist-and-playwright-dies-at-22.html?_r=0</ref> was an American author, playwright, journalist, actress and poet. She is best known for her essay <U+2018>The Opposite of Loneliness<U+2019>,<ref>http://yaledailynews.com/crosscampus/2012/05/27/keegan-the-opposite-of-loneliness/</ref> which went viral and was viewed over 1.4 million times in ninety-eight different countries after her death in a car crash just five days after she graduated magna cum laude from Yale University.<ref>http://mariashriver.com/blog/2014/04/the-opposite-of-loneliness-marina-keegan/</ref>

==Biography==
Marina Keegan was born in Boston and raised in the suburb of Wayland, Massachusetts. She attended [[Buckingham Browne & Nichols]] before matriculating to [[Yale University]] in the autumn of 2008.<ref>http://www.bbns.org/page.cfm?p=1024</ref> At Yale, Keegan majored in English and served as president of the Yale College Democrats during her junior year.<ref>http://yaledailynews.com/blog/2012/05/27/keegan-12-remembered-for-writing-activism/</ref> She was to begin a job at ''The New Yorker'' following her graduation from Yale;<ref>http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/books/2012/10/cold-pastoral-by-marina-keegan.html</ref> however, she tragically died in a car crash on Cape Cod, only five days after the ceremony.<ref>http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/cape-car-crash-kills-yale-university-graduate-marina-keegan-article-1.1085418</ref>

==''The Opposite of Loneliness''==
A collection of Keegan's works, both fiction and non-fiction, was published posthumously by Scribner on April 8, 2014.<ref>''The Opposite of Loneliness'' (New York, 2014)</ref>. The book is named after her famous graduation essay and features an introduction by the best-selling American author [[Anne Fadiman]], who was one of Keegan's professors at Yale. "The Opposite of Loneliness" was released to critical acclaim and quickly became a ''New York Times'' bestseller. The ''New York Times'' columnist Nicholas Kristof dedicated a column to the book, hailing it <U+2018>a triumph<U+2019> and urging readers to reflect on what they really want from life.<ref>The column also featured ''The Promise of a Pencil: How an Ordinary Person Can Create Extraordinary Change'' (2014), by Adam Braun. http://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/06/opinion/sunday/kristof-her-first-and-last-book.html</ref> Positive reviews of the text have been garnered from the ''Chicago Tribune'',<ref>http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2014-03-21/features/ct-books-0322-editors-choice-20140321_1_marina-keegan-loneliness-essay</ref> ''The Boston Globe'',<ref>http://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/books/2014/04/07/review-the-opposite-loneliness-essays-and-stories-marina-keegan/u9gvKsB0d25xY9cf6jDwZI/story.html</ref> and the ''Financial Times'',<ref>http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/473c6bc8-f6f3-11e3-8ed6-00144feabdc0.html#axzz36T5YHyqE</ref> among many others.

==Other notable works==
==='Even Artichokes have Doubts'===
In September, 2011, Keegan published an essay in the Yale Daily News entitled <U+2018>Even artichokes have doubts<U+2019>, lamenting the high percentage of graduates who enter into the fields of finance and consulting.<ref>http://yaledailynews.com/weekend/2011/09/30/even-artichokes-have-doubts/</ref> The piece captured the attention of author Kevin Roose, who worked for the ''New York Times''<U+2019> financial website DealBook at the time. Roose contacted Keegan and asked her to adapt her essay for DealBook, which published her piece as <U+2018>Another View: The Science and Strategy of College Recruiting<U+2019> on November 9, 2011.<ref>http://dealbook.nytimes.com/author/marina-keegan/</ref> Roose reports that it was DealBook<U+2019>s <U+2018>best-performing post in months<U+2019>.<ref>http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2014/04/remembering-marina-keegan.html</ref> He went on to feature Keegan in his book ''Young Money: Inside the Hidden World of Wall Street<U+2019>s Post-Crash Recruits'' (2014), and dedicated it to her memory. Keegan also appeared on National Public Radio's 'All Things Considered' to discuss the piece.<ref>http://www.npr.org/2012/02/05/146434854/stopping-the-brain-drain-of-the-u-s-economy</ref>

===''Independents''===
The Musical "Independants", for which Keegan had written the book, debuted at the New York International Fringe Festival in August of 2012. It was one of twelve works - out of nearly two hundred - that was selected for an encore series in September.<ref>http://www.nytimes.com/2012/08/19/theater/marina-keegans-independents-at-the-fringe.html?_r=0</ref>

==="Utility Monster"===
Keegan's play 'Utility Monster' premiered at the Wellfleet Players' Theater on Cape Cod on May 25, 2013. The play follows two fifteen-year-olds struggling with ideas of privilege and social responsibility.<ref>http://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/style/2013/05/21/marina-keegan-play-utility-monster-premieres-wellfleet-harbor-actors-theater/PnQXKInbZlhHqZNJwpWYPI/story.html</ref>

==='Cold Pastoral'===
This short story was published by ''The New Yorker'' on September 27, 2012.<ref>http://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/cold-pastoral</ref> It also appears in the book "The Opposite of Loneliness".

==='Reading Aloud'===
'Reading Aloud' was read by Rita Wolf on NPR's 'Selected Shorts' program on September 11, 2011.<ref>http://www.selectedshorts.org/fall-2011-selected-shorts-radio-schedule/</ref>

